In software engineering, when we talk about improving application performance, our minds naturally drift toward backend optimizations: upgrading server hardware, tuning database indexes, or implementing aggressive caching layers. While these are critical engineering practices, they overlook a fundamental aspect of human-computer interaction: Perceived Performance.
Imagine a high-traffic Service Desk application in a major enterprise. A support agent, handling hundreds of tickets a day, clicks the “Resolve Ticket” button. Here is what typically happens:

• The agent clicks the button.

• A loading spinner locks the screen.

• An asynchronous HTTP request travels across the network to a .NET API, updates the database, and returns a response (taking anywhere from 400ms to 1.5 seconds).

• The spinner disappears, and the UI finally updates.
Architecturally, this flow is “correct.” However, for an operations team working under strict Service Level Agreements (SLAs), that spinning wheel feels like a bottleneck. Every spinner pejoratively alters the user’s perception of the system’s speed.
What if we could reduce that network latency to absolute zero?
1. Enter Optimistic UI
Optimistic UI is a design pattern that operates on a simple assumption: “The backend will successfully process this request anyway.” Instead of waiting for the API to respond, the frontend updates its state immediately upon user interaction. The user perceives an instantaneous reaction (0ms latency), while the actual HTTP request is handled asynchronously in the background.
